context: The Rhine (Romansh: Rein, German: Rhein, French: le Rhin, Dutch: Rijn) is a European river that begins in the Swiss canton of Graubünden in the southeastern Swiss Alps, forms part of the Swiss-Austrian, Swiss-Liechtenstein border, Swiss-German and then the Franco-German border, then flows through the Rhineland and eventually empties into <a0_1>the <a0_0><a0_2><a0_3>North Sea<a0_3/><a0_2/><a0_0/> in <b7_0><b9_0>the <a5_0><a5_2><a5_3>Netherlands<b9_0/><b7_0/><a5_3/><a5_2/><a5_0/><a0_1/>. The biggest city on the river Rhine is <a1_0><a1_1><a1_2>Cologne<a1_2/>, <a4_2><a4_3><a5_1>Germany<a5_1/><a4_3/><a4_2/><a1_1/><a1_0/> with a population of more than <b10_0>1,050,000 people<b10_0/>. It is the second-longest river in <a4_1>Central and Western <a4_0>Europe<a4_1/><a4_0/> (after <a2_1>the <a2_0><a2_2><a2_3>Danube<a2_3/><a2_2/><a2_1/><a2_0/>), at about <a3_0><a3_1><a3_2><a3_3><a6_0><a6_1><a6_2><a6_3><b8_0>1,230 km<b8_0/><a6_3/><a6_2/><a6_0/><a3_3/><a3_2/> (760 mi)<a6_1/><a3_1/><a3_0/>,[note 2][note 1] with an average discharge of about <b11_0>2,900 m3/s<b11_0/> (100,000 cu ft/s).
